item.title: Police Storm Brussels Building as Antiterror Dragnet Widens
item.description: Gunfire and two explosions were heard in the Schaerbeek neighborhood, and there were preliminary reports that a suspect had been shot in the raid.
item.dc:creator: LILIA BLAISE and KIMIKO DE FREYTAS-TAMURA

item.title: China Said to Detain Several Over Letter Criticizing Xi
item.description: Four employees of Wujie News, a state-run website, and a freelance writer were reported among those held.
item.dc:creator: EDWARD WONG and CHRIS BUCKLEY
item.media:description: Chinese security officials have detained several people since a mysterious letter appeared online on March 4 demanding the resignation of President Xi Jinping, above.

item.title: Reporter’s Notebook: Obama Family Spring Break: Making History and Doing the Tango
item.description: From a historic visit in Cuba to downtime at a remote park in Argentina, the first family makes a holiday of one of President Obama’s last big trips in office.
item.dc:creator: JULIE HIRSCHFELD DAVIS
item.media:description: President Obama, with Michelle, Malia and Sasha, arriving in Buenos Aires this week.

item.title: Editorial: Human Trafficking on Trial in Thailand
item.description: The prosecution of 92 people is just a first step in reining in a huge criminal industry.
item.dc:creator: THE EDITORIAL BOARD

item.title: The Saturday Profile: Ebola, Ruthless to Families, Leaves Liberian Man Alive and Alone
item.description: Gaye Dumbai got the news that greets so many other survivors: His relatives — 13 in all — were dead. Now, more than a year later, he has his life back, but it is not the same life.
item.dc:creator: HELENE COOPER
item.media:credit: Samuel Aranda for The New York Times
item.media:description: After Gaye Dumbai recovered from Ebola in Liberia, he learned that he had lost 13 relatives to the epidemic that devastated the nation in 2014. In November last year, he rested on steps in Buchanan, Liberia.

item.title: David Dixon, Despite a Reassuring Text Message, Dies in Brussels Attacks
item.description: Mr. Dixon, 51, a British software developer and father, told his family he was safe after the airport blast — then he went to the Maelbeek subway station.
item.dc:creator: KATIE ROGERS
item.media:description: David Dixon in a photograph taken from social media.

item.title: John Kerry, in Brussels, Says ISIS Is Faltering in Mideast
item.description: The secretary of state traveled to Belgium to demonstrate American support after the attacks and said that backing for the Islamic State in the Middle East was eroding.
item.category: Islamic State in Iraq and Syria (ISIS)
item.dc:creator: SEWELL CHAN
item.media:description: Secretary of State John Kerry, second from right, during a meeting with Prime Minister Charles Michel of Belgium in Brussels on Friday.

item.title: Family of Elita Borbor Weah, Brussels Victim, Mourns One Loss, Then Another
item.description: A native of Liberia who lived in the Netherlands, Ms. Weah was on her way to the United States to attend a funeral when she was killed at the airport.
item.dc:creator: ELI ROSENBERG
item.media:description: Elita Borbor Weah, in a photograph provided by her family, at Brussels Airport on Tuesday.

item.title: Sinosphere: Hong Kong Bookseller Is Said to Return to Chinese Mainland
item.description: One day after the once-missing bookseller, Lee Bo, reappeared in Hong Kong, local news media reported that he was driven in a van to a border crossing.
item.dc:creator: AUSTIN RAMZY
item.media:description: Lee Bo, center, speaking with reporters near his home in Hong Kong on Friday. Mr. Lee was one of five people associated with Mighty Current Media to have disappeared, only to emerge in mainland China, apparently in detention.

item.title: Man Detained in North Korea Confesses to Spying for South
item.description: The man, Kim Dong-chul, who claims to be a naturalized American citizen, apologized for trying to steal military secrets in collusion with South Koreans.
item.dc:creator: CHOE SANG-HUN
item.media:description: Kim Dong-chul, center, leaving a government-arranged news conference in Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, in which he apologized for trying to steal military secrets.

item.title: Philippines Releases Ship Linked to North Korea
item.description: The Jin Teng was seized after being listed in United Nations sanctions against North Korea, but was later removed from the list, Reuters reports.
item.dc:creator: FLOYD WHALEY
item.media:description: The cargo ship Jin Teng docked at Subic Bay in the Philippines after it was seized under United Nations sanctions.

item.title: Henri Bonneau, French Wine Producer Known for Châteauneuf-du-Pape, Dies at 77
item.description: Mr. Bonneau, a 12th-generation vigneron, rejected modern methods to issue powerful wines that recalled how they might have tasted a century or two ago.
item.dc:creator: ERIC ASIMOV
item.media:description: Henri Bonneau had little use for modern methods of wine production.

item.title: Egypt Implicates 4 Men Killed by Police in Death of Italian Student
item.description: The Interior Ministry said property belonging to a student who disappeared in January was found at the home of a gang member’s sister. Many worldwide had blamed Egyptian security forces.
item.dc:creator: KAREEM FAHIM
item.media:description: People holding an Italian flag with photos of Giulio Regeni at a demonstration outside Egypt’s embassy in Rome last month.

item.title: Russia and the U.S. Agree to Try to Bolster Cease-Fire in Syria
item.description: Secretary of State John Kerry, who met with President Vladimir V. Putin for four hours in Moscow, said the improvements in Syria since the cease-fire started on Feb. 27 were “not sufficient.”
item.dc:creator: NEIL MacFARQUHAR
item.media:description: Secretary of State John Kerry met with his Russian counterpart, Sergey V. Lavrov, in Moscow, on Thursday.

item.title: World Briefing: Congo Republic: President Is Re-elected
item.description: President Denis Sassou-Nguesso has won a new five-year term with more than 60 percent of the vote, the interior minister said, but the opposition rejected the outcome.
item.dc:creator: REUTERS

item.title: Brussels Suicide Bomber Wasn’t One of Ours, Bahamas Says
item.description: Khalid el-Bakraoui, one of the suicide bombers in Brussels, was listed as a Bahamian citizen in an Interpol arrest warrant because of a “clerical error.”
item.dc:creator: SEWELL CHAN

item.title: World Briefing: Angola: Yellow Fever Outbreak Kills 178
item.description: More than 450 people have been infected by the disease since December, the World Health Organization said, and there is a global vaccine shortage.
